		\begin{flushleft} 
		
			\textbf{3.3 Line Breaks, Spaces and Indents} \bigskip			

			\LaTeX{} mainly disregards any in-code spaces or line breaks, i.e. they have no visual impact on the actual text document. 
			For example, a sentence can be spread across several lines of code without disrupting the text output.
			In the same way, any number of spaces can be inserted between code elements without them being transferred to the text document. 
			The only time where spacing matters is for commands, as they cannot be broken up. Compare:

		\end{flushleft}
					
