			% Quotation 
			
			Quotation marks are prone to displaying errors, depending on the editor that is used. 
			
			One of the safest ways to include quotation marks in a text is via the \textit{\textbackslash enquote\{\}} function from the 
			\foreignlanguage{english}{\enquote*{csquotes}} package, 
			which can be conjoined with the \textit{\textbackslash foreignlanguage\{\}} function from the \foreignlanguage{english}{\enquote*{babel}} package to 
			allow for language appropriate quotation.
			Both packages need to be loaded in via the \textit{\textbackslash usepackage\{\}} command (see XXX) in the preamble and can be
			modified with optional arguments such as the desired languages for the \foreignlanguage{english}{\enquote*{babel}} package and 
			different styles for the \foreignlanguage{english}{\enquote*{csquotes}} package (for example, \foreignlanguage{english}{\enquote*{autostyle}} 
			continuously adapts the quote style to the current document language).
			
			\bigskip

			The standard command \textit{\textbackslash enquote\{\}} inserts double quotation marks, but can be modified with an asterisk to
			switch to single quotation marks (i.e. \textit{\textbackslash enquote*\{\}}). 
			Finally, quotes may be nested with \textit{\textbackslash enquote\{\textbackslash enquote\{\}\}} to achieve quotation within quotation.	

			\bigskip

		\end{flushleft}
					
